## 3. Ticket Handling

### 3.1 Lifecycle

1. **Create**: Correct type (Epic, Feature, Bug, Task), project, **component**. Set **component** = app/area (e.g. Slack, Google Gemini AI). Use summary format `[app]: [what is done]` so the title matches the component.
2. **Triage**: Priority, assignee (or leave unassigned per process), sprint/backlog.
3. **Refine**: Acceptance criteria, estimate, dependencies.
4. **Progress**: Move through workflow; keep status and assignee up to date.
5. **Complete**: Resolution, time tracking if used, link to deploy.
6. **Close/Archive**: When done and no longer needed on the board.

### 3.2 Ticket Types (Integration Engineering)

| Type | Use when |
|------|----------|
| **Epic** | Large initiative or theme; contains Features, Bugs, Tasks |
| **Feature** | New product capability; has acceptance criteria |
| **Task** | Small, distinct piece of work (e.g. tech task, spike) |
| **Bug** | Problem or error; needs fix |
| **Sub-task** | Part of a parent Feature, Task, or Bug |

### 3.3 Handling Blocked Items

- Use "blocked by" link or label (e.g. `blocked`).
- Optional status "Blocked" or clear convention (e.g. comment + label).
- Unblock when dependency is resolved; update status and remove block.

### 3.4 Templates

- **Feature**: Goal, context, acceptance criteria, out of scope, links.
- **Bug**: Steps to reproduce, expected vs actual, environment, severity.
- **Task**: Objective, steps or checklist, definition of done.

### 3.5 New ticket creation

Use the following structure when creating **Task** or **Feature** issues. Reference: [IEN-14682](https://make.atlassian.net/browse/IEN-14682).

#### Summary

- **Always** use the format `[app]: [what is done]`.
- `[app]` = the ticket **component** (e.g. Slack, Google Gemini AI). Set the JIRA component to match the app in the title.
- Examples: `Slack: AI Learning`, `Google Gemini AI: Inject current date in Simple text prompt`.

#### Description structure (Markdown)

Use these sections in order. All sections use Markdown; bullets use `*` or `-`.

| Section | Purpose | Required |
|--------|---------|----------|
| **Goal** | What we are doing, why, and when (context and objective). Include API or vendor documentation links here when relevant (e.g. deprecation notices, Service Account docs). | Yes |
| **Acceptance** | Bullet list of acceptance criteria (what “done” means). | Yes |
| **Notes** | References: Slack thread URL, design doc, related tickets, etc. | Optional |

**Task** — use as above. Keep Goal and Acceptance concise; add Definition of done bullets under Acceptance if useful.

**Feature** — use the same structure; add **Out of scope** (bullet list) when it helps avoid ambiguity.

#### Example (minimal)

```markdown
Goal

This is the goal — what, why, when.

Acceptance

* acceptance 1
* acceptance 2
* acceptance 3

Notes

* Slack thread - URL
* any reference
```

#### Checklist when creating a Task or Feature

- [ ] **Summary**: Format `[app]: [what is done]`; **component** set to match `[app]`.
- [ ] **Goal**: Filled with context and objective; API or vendor documentation links in Goal when the ticket stems from external/API changes (e.g. deprecation, new auth).
- [ ] **Acceptance**: Bullet list of criteria (and Definition of done if needed).
- [ ] **Due Date**: If the source mentions a deadline (e.g. "must be done before DDMMYYYY", "removal date March 3, 2027"), set the **Due Date** custom field in JIRA to that date.
- [ ] **Notes**: References added when relevant (e.g. Slack, Confluence, related issues). Do not add a reminder about creating a CXPDOC2 ticket when moving to Documentation — that is default practice.

### 3.6 Lessons learned (creating from external requests)

When creating IEN tickets from vendor announcements, deprecation notices, or API changes:

* **Due Date**: If the source states a deadline in any form (e.g. "must be done before 03.03.2027", "full removal date March 3, 2027", "by end of Q2 2026"), set the JIRA **Due Date** custom field to that date so the board reflects the real deadline.
* **API / documentation in Goal**: If the request includes a link to API docs, developer guides, or vendor documentation (e.g. Service Account setup, migration guide), put that reference **directly in the Goal section** so it is visible with the context. Use Notes for secondary references (Slack, Confluence, related tickets).
* **CXPDOC2 workflow**: Do not add a note in the ticket like "when in Documentation, create parallel CXPDOC2 ticket". Creating a CXPDOC2 ticket when an IEN item moves to Documentation is standard practice and does not need to be repeated in every ticket.

